authors.description: Jonathan Eyal was born in Romania, but has lived most of his life in Britain. Educated at Oxford and London universities, his initial training was in international law and relations, in which he obtained both his first degree and his Master's with a Distinction. His doctorate, completed at Oxford in 1987, analysed relations between ethnic minorities in Eastern Europe. After teaching at Oxford for three years, Dr Eyal was appointed a researcher at the Royal United Services Institute for Defence Studies in London. Since 1990, Dr Eyal has been Director of Studies at the Institute. Dr Eyal has authored books on military relations in the Balkans and Eastern Europe, and became a regular commentator for The Guardian newspaper in London. He started writing for The Straits Times in 2001, and is currently the paper's Europe Correspondent. He is fluent in French, Romanian, Italian, Hungarian and German.

authors.description:
Chang May Choon has been a journalist with Singapore Press Holdings for 15 years, starting with The New Paper where she built a reputation as the paper's in-house Korean guru with the weekly column Hallyu Buzz. In 2008, she crossed over to explore multimedia reporting with The Straits Times RazorTV, where she produced news videos on topics ranging from politics to local news, lifestyle and entertainment. She counts the 2011 Singapore general elections and presidential election as the most exciting time of her multimedia journalism career. She returned to print reporting last year and was posted to Seoul in May 2015 to start The Straits Times' first bureau in South Korea. The Nanyang Technological University journalism school alumnus hopes to be the bridge between the two countries, covering Korean news with a Singapore perspective and producing her own videos.
May Choon's "love affair" with South Korea started with watching melodramas and she flew to Seoul in 2005 on a three-month sabbatical to learn the Korean language at Korea University. Even when she was away, she maintained her presence in The New Paper with a 10-part column called Seoul Searching, giving her take on Korean culture and people. In 2009, she married a Korean photographer. They have a lovely daughter.
authors.name: Chang May Choon

articleData.longHeadline: Today in Pictures, March 7, 2023
articleData.headline: Today in Pictures, March 7, 2023
articleData.subHeadline: An inflatable decoy of an M1 Abrams tank, Makha Bucha Day in Pathum Thani province outside Bangkok and other photos from around the world in Today in Pictures.

images.caption: An inflatable decoy of an M1 Abrams tank on display during a media presentation in Decin, Czech Republic, on March 6, 2023. A Czech company producing inflatable weapon decoys, such as Himars rocket launchers, has seen profits soar since the Russian invasion of Ukraine started in 2022. The Inflatech company based in the northern Czech city of Decin and founded eight years ago makes more than 30 types of inflatable weapons.
Attendants serving tea inside the Great Hall of the People in Beijing, China, ahead of the second plenary session of the National People's Congress on Tuesday.

An indigenous individual of Raramuri (Tarahumara) competing in the Caballo Blanco Ultramarathon in the Tarahumara mountains in Urique, Chihuahua state, Mexico, on March 5, 2023. Hundreds of athletes compete against the tireless long-distance runners of the indigenous community in the mountains of north-western Mexico. Mexican and the United States organisers announced 1,200 participants for the 20th anniversary of the ultramarathon, for which festivities began on the eve.

A Buddhist monk lighting up a candle at the Wat Phra Dhammakaya temple during a ceremony to commemorate Makha Bucha Day, a day for honouring the third lunar month in Buddhist traditions, in Pathum Thani province outside Bangkok, Thailand, on March 6, 2023.
Students daubing one another with gulal, or coloured powder, as they celebrate Holi, the Hindu spring festival of colours, at the Guru Nanak Dev University in Amritsar, India, on March 6, 2023.

A man taking a picture of a mosaic image of a pike fish at Nagatinsky Zaton subway station in Moscow, Russia, on March 6, 2023. The newly opened Big Circle Line is a 70km loop that links 31 stations with each station having its own unique design.
An aerial view of mudflats, revealed during the low tide after the River Medway ebbed, near Gillingham in south-east England on March 2, 2023.

A model presenting a playful and sculptural look from the Louis Vuitton Womenswear Fall-Winter 2023-2024 collection that explores notions of French style during Paris Fashion Week in Paris, France, on March 6, 2023.
